- "Most recently accessed" implies the report is ordered by name in descending order, which might be a proxy for recency in this context;
- "Frequently used" refers to having more than one access entry;
- "Contains multiple data entries" means the report has more than one data entry associated with it;
- "Involves multiple user roles" indicates that more than one role is associated with the user;
- "Generated multiple times" means the report has been generated more than once.

- 'Unique users' refers to the distinct number of users who have accessed the report;
- 'Views' and 'downloads' are types of access where 'view' means the report was opened and 'download' means the report was downloaded;
- 'Desktop access percentage' is the proportion of accesses that were made from a desktop device, expressed as a percentage.

- 'Researchers' are users with the role 'researcher';
- 'Subscriptions' refer to the reports a user is subscribed to;
- 'Linked to areas' means the reports are associated with specific COVID-19 data entries for those areas;
- 'More new cases than the average' means the number of new cases is greater than the average number of new cases across all data entries.

sql:
SELECT report_id, COUNT(log_id) AS access_log_count
FROM report_access_logs
GROUP BY report_id;

SELECT 
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM users) AS total_users, 
  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM roles) AS total_roles;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT user_id) AS total_active_users
FROM (
  SELECT user_id FROM report_access_logs
  UNION
  SELECT user_id FROM data_access_logs
) AS combined_access_logs;

